    </blockquote>
    <p>
      The diagram also shows “Native Apps” which is a popular term used to refer to apps installed directly on phones and ipads. These apps have some similarities to both traditionally installed desktop apps and server powered web apps. Like web apps, the native apps can be easily accessed/downloaded using the internet and they also use the internet to access any needed server resources. But native apps, like traditional desktop apps, need to be explicitly downloaded (usually from app stores like Applie Itunes and Google Play) and installed before they can be used. Also, they don’t use the browser as a GUI. Instead, native apps directl integrate with the mobile devices underlying operating system (IOS, Android etc) to present its GUI. This makes them faster and more powerful, in some ways, than web apps on phones and tables. But web apps remain very effective for many types of apps used on both mobile and desktop computers.
    </p>
    
    <p>
      Compared to the previous generation of desktop apps which were distributed using CDs and other physical media, web apps and native apps have the characteristic that they can be easily downloaded and accessed by any user with the right credentials (username/password) from any computer with internet access. The, so-called “cloud” is this collection of web/native apps which, just like real natural clouds, appear omni-present and continuously evolving. Another important term,  Software As A Service (SAAS), is a phrase popularized by business minded technology commentators to refer to either web apps, native apps or their closely related counterpart “Application Programming Interfaces” or APIs. More on this next.
    </p>
    
